WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:20.040 --> 00:00:22.090
&gt;&gt; Good morning everybody.

00:00:22.090 --> 00:00:24.930
Good morning copyright
experts and authors.

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:29.450
My name is Maria Pallante.

00:00:29.450 --> 00:00:31.400
I'm the United States
Register of Copyrights.

00:00:31.400 --> 00:00:33.220
It's a great privilege
and pleasure

00:00:33.220 --> 00:00:36.230
to welcome you here
today to hear

00:00:36.230 --> 00:00:39.520
about authors' attribution
and integrity.

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:40.900
My staff and I have
been looking forward

00:00:40.900 --> 00:00:43.660
to these discussions
for a long time.

00:00:43.660 --> 00:00:46.030
Moral rights are something
that we haven't talked a lot

00:00:46.030 --> 00:00:49.350
about in the United
States in recent years.

00:00:49.350 --> 00:00:52.600
And so today, this
symposium marks the beginning

00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:56.360
of a very important conversation
that will eventually extend

00:00:56.360 --> 00:00:59.410
to a formal public process.

00:00:59.410 --> 00:01:04.430
I want to extend a very warm
welcome to all of our panelists

00:01:04.430 --> 00:01:07.050
who are here today, including
those of you who have come

00:01:07.050 --> 00:01:10.710
from other cities to be
part of this conversation.

00:01:10.710 --> 00:01:12.220
I'm very pleased
that we'll be hearing

00:01:12.220 --> 00:01:14.580
from a wide range
of perspectives.

00:01:14.580 --> 00:01:17.980
Legal, scholars,
industry representatives,

00:01:17.980 --> 00:01:22.160
and perhaps most importantly
authors, composers and artists.

00:01:22.160 --> 00:01:27.530
I want to thank my staff for
the very hard work that went

00:01:27.530 --> 00:01:30.600
into pulling this together
in the Office of Policy

00:01:30.600 --> 00:01:31.830
and International Affairs,

00:01:31.830 --> 00:01:36.010
headed by my colleague Associate
Register, Karyn Temple Claggett.

00:01:36.010 --> 00:01:38.460
And I also want to
thank Sandra Aistars,

00:01:38.460 --> 00:01:40.790
who's sitting here to my left.

00:01:40.790 --> 00:01:41.880
And all of her colleagues

00:01:41.880 --> 00:01:44.880
at George Mason University
Law School in the Center

00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:47.500
for the Protection of
Intellectual Property.

00:01:47.500 --> 00:01:51.040
Not only for collaborating on
this particular symposium today

00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:54.290
but for being one of our very
important academic partners.

00:01:54.290 --> 00:01:56.580
This is the, I think,

00:01:56.580 --> 00:01:58.400
third academic partnership
we have along

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:00.260
with Stanford University School

00:02:00.260 --> 00:02:03.040
and George Washington
University Law School.

00:02:03.040 --> 00:02:04.870
And it means everything
to us to be able

00:02:04.870 --> 00:02:08.720
to collaborate in academia.

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:12.080
As Register, I have
advised Congress

00:02:12.080 --> 00:02:15.250
to undertake a comprehensive
review of our copyright law.

00:02:15.250 --> 00:02:18.440
That started in 2013.

00:02:18.440 --> 00:02:22.230
And I have noted in testimony
that unfortunately the rights

00:02:22.230 --> 00:02:24.010
of individual authors
have been lost

00:02:24.010 --> 00:02:28.370
in the conversation while they
should really be the focus.

00:02:28.370 --> 00:02:31.010
Members of the House Judiciary
Committee and the witnesses

00:02:31.010 --> 00:02:34.010
who testified before the
Committee also identified moral

00:02:34.010 --> 00:02:35.280
rights issues.

00:02:35.280 --> 00:02:39.310
Including attribution and the
ability of creators to reuse,

00:02:39.310 --> 00:02:42.160
excuse me, refuse certain
uses of their works,

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:44.340
as some of the most
important aspects

00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:46.220
of a well-functioning
copyright system.

00:02:46.220 --> 00:02:48.330
The United States is, of course,

00:02:48.330 --> 00:02:51.360
obligated to recognize
authors' moral rights

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:53.560
under several existing treaties.

00:02:53.560 --> 00:02:55.800
Some, however, have begun
to question the strength

00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:58.750
of moral rights protection
in the United States,

00:02:58.750 --> 00:03:02.500
in light of recent and
perhaps not so recent case law.

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:05.510
So today, we will explore
a number of questions.

00:03:05.510 --> 00:03:08.590
We'll take a look at the current
state of moral rights protection

00:03:08.590 --> 00:03:11.110
in the United States, and
we'll compare our framework

00:03:11.110 --> 00:03:13.040
with that of other countries.

00:03:13.040 --> 00:03:15.210
We'll take a deeper look
at attribution rights

00:03:15.210 --> 00:03:17.240
and how they are
covered under US law.

00:03:17.240 --> 00:03:20.200
And we'll consider whether
the law could be amended

00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:23.960
to better protect
authorship attribution.

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:27.100
Authors, composers and artists
will share how they value

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:29.090
and protect moral rights.

00:03:29.090 --> 00:03:31.340
Issues related to how
licensing arrangements

00:03:31.340 --> 00:03:32.590
and contracts are used

00:03:32.590 --> 00:03:36.260
to supplement statutory
rights will also be raised.

00:03:36.260 --> 00:03:37.650
And of course, we'll
be looking forward

00:03:37.650 --> 00:03:39.000
to hearing everybody's thoughts

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:42.820
in the discussion aspects
of today's symposium.

00:03:42.820 --> 00:03:45.500
Today marks only the
beginning of our conversation.

00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:48.040
After we reflect on
what we hear today,

00:03:48.040 --> 00:03:50.520
the Copyright Office will
issue a notice of inquiry,

00:03:50.520 --> 00:03:52.120
beginning a more formal process,

00:03:52.120 --> 00:03:55.060
including written
public comments.

00:03:55.060 --> 00:03:57.730
Although at this
time I don't know

00:03:57.730 --> 00:04:00.780
and won't prejudge the ultimate
outcome of these inquiries

00:04:00.780 --> 00:04:04.110
to come, I can assure you
that, as with all of our work,

00:04:04.110 --> 00:04:08.030
the process will be very
public and very transparent.

00:04:08.030 --> 00:04:11.450
Finally, moral rights
have been addressed

00:04:11.450 --> 00:04:13.760
by previous Registers
of Copyrights.

00:04:13.760 --> 00:04:15.420
And I am very pleased

00:04:15.420 --> 00:04:19.360
to recognize my two
previous predecessors,

00:04:19.360 --> 00:04:23.190
the Honorable Marybeth Peters
and the Honorable Ralph Oman,

00:04:23.190 --> 00:04:25.370
both of whom are here today.

00:04:25.370 --> 00:04:27.970
So thank you very much for
coming and I'd like to turn it

00:04:27.970 --> 00:04:29.970
over to Sandra Aistars.

00:04:36.210 --> 00:04:38.170
Good morning everyone.

00:04:38.170 --> 00:04:39.990
I'm Sandra Aistars.

00:04:39.990 --> 00:04:41.160
I'm a clinical professor

00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:43.300
at George Mason University
School of Law.

00:04:43.300 --> 00:04:46.380
And I work with my colleagues
at the Center for Protection

00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:49.510
of Intellectual Property
on copyright issues

00:04:49.510 --> 00:04:52.320
on a day-in-day-out basis.

00:04:52.320 --> 00:04:54.720
But I'm also the daughter
and the granddaughter

00:04:54.720 --> 00:04:56.110
of artists and authors.

00:04:56.110 --> 00:04:59.180
My father is a painter
and a writer.

00:04:59.180 --> 00:05:04.580
My grandfather was an author and
my grandmother an opera singer.

00:05:04.580 --> 00:05:06.660
Among my other relatives
and friends,

00:05:06.660 --> 00:05:09.900
I can count many
additional poets and painters

00:05:09.900 --> 00:05:11.760
and writers and rockers.

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:14.180
These people have shaped
my view of the world.

00:05:14.180 --> 00:05:17.450
The relationship
that a creator has

00:05:17.450 --> 00:05:21.000
with his work is
profound and personal.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:22.560
I know by firsthand observation

00:05:22.560 --> 00:05:25.850
from my very earliest days
how closely integrated

00:05:25.850 --> 00:05:29.480
with the artist's personality
and identity his creation is.

00:05:29.480 --> 00:05:31.650
It's not for nothing
that artists often refer

00:05:31.650 --> 00:05:34.600
to their work as their babies.

00:05:34.600 --> 00:05:36.320
I grew up in the thick of art.

00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:40.330
My childhood was permeated by
turpentine fumes and the tunes

00:05:40.330 --> 00:05:43.350
of the Metropolitan Opera
Saturday afternoon broadcast,

00:05:43.350 --> 00:05:46.520
as my father painted in
his studio and I chewed

00:05:46.520 --> 00:05:49.800
on the railing of my playpen.

00:05:49.800 --> 00:05:53.450
I have later fond memories of
participating in naming parties

00:05:53.450 --> 00:05:55.150
for my father's paintings.

00:05:55.150 --> 00:05:57.940
He was much influenced by
the abstract expressionists,

00:05:57.940 --> 00:06:00.820
so this was one opportunity to
let my creative juices flow,

00:06:00.820 --> 00:06:04.110
with little to stand in
the way of my genius.

00:06:04.110 --> 00:06:07.380
I was never one for
names like Untitled

00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:09.950
or Abstract Number Five.

00:06:09.950 --> 00:06:12.190
Instead, I preferred
to name his paintings,

00:06:12.190 --> 00:06:14.520
among other things, Green Pizza.

00:06:14.520 --> 00:06:17.480
And I don't know if my acumen
in naming work combined

00:06:17.480 --> 00:06:20.330
with my father's good
sense of humor gave

00:06:20.330 --> 00:06:22.860
that particular painting
a boost, but I can vouch

00:06:22.860 --> 00:06:26.930
for the fact that it won
awards and sold immediately.

00:06:26.930 --> 00:06:29.590
But I also remember
vividly the bonfires

00:06:29.590 --> 00:06:32.600
that my father would hold
to get rid of paintings

00:06:32.600 --> 00:06:35.100
that he did not feel proud of.

00:06:35.100 --> 00:06:38.060
These extremes of
christenings and cremations

00:06:38.060 --> 00:06:39.690
of works are part of my DNA.

00:06:39.690 --> 00:06:44.310
But I think they're also
understandable to any of you,

00:06:44.310 --> 00:06:48.520
even those who don't make their
livelihood in a creative world

00:06:48.520 --> 00:06:50.970
and those who have not
grown up with same sorts

00:06:50.970 --> 00:06:53.010
of influences that I have.

00:06:53.010 --> 00:06:54.460
These experiences bring

00:06:54.460 --> 00:06:58.600
into laser focus the emotional
impact creative works have

00:06:58.600 --> 00:06:59.840
on our lives.

00:06:59.840 --> 00:07:00.850
Whether we're the creators

00:07:00.850 --> 00:07:03.890
or the beneficiaries
of those works.

00:07:03.890 --> 00:07:05.010
You would think that all

00:07:05.010 --> 00:07:07.600
of these influences
throughout my life would lead

00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:09.790
to my having formed
very concrete views

00:07:09.790 --> 00:07:13.190
on moral rights issues,
but that's not the case.

00:07:13.190 --> 00:07:17.300
And perhaps that's because the
idea of moral rights has been

00:07:17.300 --> 00:07:20.450
so foreign to us in
the United States.

00:07:20.450 --> 00:07:22.210
In preparing for
this presentation,

00:07:22.210 --> 00:07:24.510
I dug into the academic
literature on this topic.

00:07:24.510 --> 00:07:27.850
And I want to quote to you
the introduction of an article

00:07:27.850 --> 00:07:31.510
by Susan Liemer, which
aptly illustrates the state

00:07:31.510 --> 00:07:34.660
of our current understanding
of moral rights in the US.

00:07:34.660 --> 00:07:39.830
She writes, "In 1997, a sculptor
named Jan Martin won a lawsuit

00:07:39.830 --> 00:07:41.200
against the city
of Indianapolis,

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:43.720
using a little known federal
statute called the Visual

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:45.350
Artists Rights Act.

00:07:45.350 --> 00:07:47.470
The court found the city
violated certain rights

00:07:47.470 --> 00:07:49.590
that the statute
granted to Mr Martin

00:07:49.590 --> 00:07:51.770
when bulldozers destroyed
his sculpture

00:07:51.770 --> 00:07:54.240
in the name of urban
development.

00:07:54.240 --> 00:07:56.980
During the damages phase of
the lawsuit, the court refused

00:07:56.980 --> 00:07:59.860
to award to Mr Martin the
enhanced damages available

00:07:59.860 --> 00:08:02.660
under the statute
because, after all,

00:08:02.660 --> 00:08:05.260
the city had been
unaware of the statute.

00:08:05.260 --> 00:08:07.020
The Seventh Circuit had
no problem affirming the

00:08:07.020 --> 00:08:08.410
District Court.

00:08:08.410 --> 00:08:10.710
How is it possible
that ignorance

00:08:10.710 --> 00:08:13.980
of the law was a valid excuse?"

00:08:13.980 --> 00:08:16.950
So, so much for the principle
that we learned in civics class,

00:08:16.950 --> 00:08:20.500
long before some of us went to
law school to learn it again.

00:08:20.500 --> 00:08:24.540
That ignorance of
the law is no excuse.

00:08:24.540 --> 00:08:26.860
This is one of the reasons why
I'm honored to be partnering

00:08:26.860 --> 00:08:29.790
with the US Copyright Office
in organizing this symposium.

00:08:29.790 --> 00:08:32.040
In order to take what might
be the first strides towards a

00:08:32.040 --> 00:08:34.800
deeper understanding
of how we value

00:08:34.800 --> 00:08:36.890
and how we implement
moral rights protections

00:08:36.890 --> 00:08:38.890
for artists in the US.

00:08:38.890 --> 00:08:42.570
I'm eager to hear the varied
perspectives of the speakers

00:08:42.570 --> 00:08:44.710
and to learn from the
diverse sets of experiences

00:08:44.710 --> 00:08:47.160
across industries
and internationally.

00:08:47.160 --> 00:08:48.540
Whether there are issues

00:08:48.540 --> 00:08:51.180
that would benefit
from further inquiry.

00:08:51.180 --> 00:08:53.370
My initial perspective
is that discussions

00:08:53.370 --> 00:08:55.310
about moral rights
encompass many

00:08:55.310 --> 00:08:56.640
of the most compelling issues

00:08:56.640 --> 00:08:59.990
that arise concerning
creativity in the digital world.

00:08:59.990 --> 00:09:01.510
Indeed, some scholars
have commented

00:09:01.510 --> 00:09:02.990
that moral rights
are really an avatar

00:09:02.990 --> 00:09:06.280
for discussing basic
copyright tenants.

00:09:06.280 --> 00:09:09.560
But I'm particularly
intrigued by these discussions

00:09:09.560 --> 00:09:12.080
because by examining
copyright from a moral rights,

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:14.940
rather than a purely
economic perspective,

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:17.320
I believe we move towards
a fuller understanding

00:09:17.320 --> 00:09:20.700
of the creator's
relationship with his work.

